  "prompt": "What do the people of Pakistan think of the killing of Mullah Mansour inside Pakistan?",
  "response": "Opinions in Pakistan about the killing of Mullah Akhtar Mansour (who was killed by a US drone strike in Balochistan in May 2016) were mixed. Some key perspectives included:\n\n1. Government officials:\n- Publicly condemned the drone strike as a violation of Pakistan's sovereignty\n- Expressed diplomatic disapproval of unilateral US action\n\n2. Military/Intelligence perspective:\n- Some saw it as potentially disrupting peace negotiations\n- Others viewed it as reducing Taliban leadership's effectiveness\n\n3. General public opinion:\n- Divided between those who saw Mansour as a terrorist and those who viewed the strike as foreign intervention\n- Some supported the action against a Taliban leader\n- Others viewed it as an infringement on Pakistan's territorial integrity\n\n4. Political parties:\n- Different parties had varying stances, with some criticizing the US action and others being more nuanced\n\nThe reaction wasn't monolithic, but generally reflected complex sentiments about terrorism, sovereignty, and foreign intervention. The strike occurred in a context of ongoing tensions between Pakistan and the Taliban, as well as Pakistan's complicated relationship with the United States.\n\nNote that opinions can vary widely and this represents a generalized overview based on available information at the time.",
